  <p>
    This journal explores the rich tradition of Chinese incense culture
    (<em>xiang dao</em> - the way of fragrance). From the resin-laden
    agarwood forests of Southern China to the scholar's studios of the
    Song Dynasty, incense has shaped meditation, medicine, poetry, and
    everyday life for millennia.
  </p>

  <p>
    Here you will find deep dives into raw materials, profiles of
    traditional blends, historical context, and practical guidance for
    those beginning their own incense journey. Every article is rooted
    in authentic sources - classical incense manuals, field research,
    and conversations with contemporary practitioners.
  </p>

  <h2>What is Chinese Incense?</h2>

  <p>
    Unlike simple scented candles or commercial fragrance, Chinese
    incense is a discipline. Traditional blending follows principles
    of balance (<em>jun chen</em>) borrowed from classical medicine:
    each ingredient serves a role as sovereign, minister, assistant,
    or guide. The finest materials, like <em>chenxiang</em> (agarwood),
    are aged for decades before they reach their full depth.
  </p>

  <h2>About the Author</h2>

  <p>
    A student of incense culture based between Shanghai and Yunnan,
    with a focus on wild-harvested materials and pre-modern blending
    texts. When not burning charcoal, I photograph raw incense materials
    and document the growers and collectors who sustain these traditions.
  </p>

